entricular diastole","Has two cusps and remains open throughout the cardiac cycle","Has four cusps and closes during ventricular diastole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mitral valve is a bicuspid valve that \u003Cstrong\u003Ehas two cusps and closes during ventricular systole\u003C/strong\u003E. This closure prevents backflow of blood from the left ventricle into the left atrium when ventricular pressure exceeds atrial pressure during systole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas three cusps and closes during atrial systole\u003C/strong\u003E - The mitral valve has two cusps, not three, and closes during ventricular, not atrial systole\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas three cusps and closes during ventricular diastole\u003C/strong\u003E - The mitral valve opens during diastole to allow ventricular filling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas two cusps and remains open throughout the cardiac cycle\u003C/strong\u003E - The valve must close during systole to prevent retrograde flow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas four cusps and closes during ventricular diastole\u003C/strong\u003E - The valve has two cusps and closes during systole\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two cusps of the mitral valve (anterior and posterior) are anchored by chordae tendineae to prevent prolapse. The valve opens during ventricular diastole when atrial pressure exceeds ventricular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mitral valve prevents the movement of blood during ventricular systole from the left ventricle back to the left atrium.","The mitral valve has two cusps (anterior and posterior) while other cardiac valves have three cusps.","The mitral valve opens during ventricular diastole to allow blood flow 